The paper deals with source coding, which is a subfield of information theory (cs.IT). It specifically focuses on the performance of integer-forcing source coding, which is a method for compressing correlated Gaussian sources, making cs.MM (multimedia) a likely sub-category as well. The paper also discusses the application of this method to antenna inputs in a Rayleigh fading environment, which falls under the sub-categories of cs.SI (signal processing) and cs.NI (networking and internet architecture). Finally, the paper provides performance guarantees for distributed source coding, which is a topic in control and systems engineering, making cs.SY (systems and control) a possible sub-category as well.
